                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.114 Netherlands/43b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Emmet</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-08T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 8, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>47. Commander B. M. Thompson, a representative of the Treasury Department, will
                    visit you in near future to discuss question of obtaining cooperation of
                    Netherlands Government in prevention of alcohol and liquor smuggling. Please
                    extend appropriate assistance.</p>
                <p>With reference to your despatch No. 148, January 24, 1935 after discussing matter
                    with Commander Thompson endeavor, in your discretion, to have Netherlands
                    Government extend provision requiring bonds for production of landing
                    certificate to include all vessels carrying spirits to any country. Present
                    system of withholding information regarding exports of spirits facilitates
                    smuggling and reduces legitimate exports. Bonds for production of landing
                    certificates now required by Canada, Cuba, British West Indies, Newfoundland,
                    British Honduras, and St. Pierre-Miquelon, leaving European ports as main
                    sources of alcohol for smuggling traffic.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
